<p>Now, you have 6 subnets prepared.
<a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="OpsBridge2019.02Subnet7.jpg" src="/mediawiki/images/8/8f/OpsBridge2019.02Subnet7.jpg" width="1277" height="561" data-file-width="1277" data-file-height="561"></a>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Associate_an_Internet_gateway_table_routing_with_three_public_subnets">Associate an Internet gateway table routing with three public subnets</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=Operations_Bridge:2019.05/SubNOpsB&amp;veaction=edit&amp;section=6" class="mw-editsection-visualeditor" title="Edit section: Associate an Internet gateway table routing with three public subnets">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-divider"> | </span><a href="/mediawiki/index.php?title=Operations_Bridge:2019.05/SubNOpsB&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Associate an Internet gateway table routing with three public subnets">edit source</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>To associate an Internet gateway route table with your public subnets, make sure your VPC has an Internet gateway attached first.
Go to the three public subnets you prepared and associate the subnets with the route table. This route table attaches to the Internet gateway.
</p><p><a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="OpsBridge2019.02Subnet7.jpg" src="/mediawiki/images/8/8f/OpsBridge2019.02Subnet7.jpg" width="1277" height="561" data-file-width="1277" data-file-height="561"></a>
</p>
